LAGOS – While the sudden elimination of Nigeria from the ongoing Africa Cup of Nations (AFCON) in Cameroon has continued to dominate space, the Nigeria Football Federation (NFF) has been charged to forget about what happened in the competition and focus on how the country could qualify for the 2022 World Cup in Qatar. Recall that in the playoff draws conducted in Cameroon last Saturday, Nigeria will play Ghana for one of the tickets for the Mundial in what is the rekindling of the age-long rivalry between the Super Eagles and the Black Stars However, since Tunisia surprisingly eliminated Nigeria at the round of 16 stage of the ongoing AFCON, the talk had centred on what went wrong but Friday Ekpo, an AFCON third place winner with the Super Eagles in Senegal in 1992, said it was high time Nigerians now focus their attention on how the team would qualify for the World Cup, admonishing the NFF to now channel their energies on how to effectively prepare the team to overcome the Ghana hurdle. NWW Technical Commission Re-Appoints Igali As Member FIFA Sends Condolences After AFCON Crush “What is most important now is to plan ahead because the AFCON door is closed already. We have World Cup playoff in March and all efforts should be devoted to it. “NFF should look at ways to effectively prepare the team to overcome Ghana because still talking about what happened in Cameroon may affect our preparations towards the playoff,” he responded to our correspondent when his views were sought.